  "GEN_EPIGENETICS_001": {
    "id": "GEN_EPIGENETICS_001",
    "node_type": "genetics",
    "version": "1.0",
    "name": "Epigenetics (The Master Switchboard)",
    "mechanism": "The study of how behaviors and environment cause changes that affect the WAY genes work, without changing the underlying DNA sequence.",
    "polymorphism_impact": "Two primary mechanisms:\n1. DNA Methylation: Adding a methyl group to a gene 'turns it off' (silences it). Removing it 'turns it on'.\n2. Histone Modification: DNA is wrapped around histone proteins. Tightly wrapped DNA cannot be read (turned off); loosely wrapped DNA is actively read (turned on).",
    "biological_consequences": [
      "This is why identical twins can have completely different diseases. One twin's diet turned on an autoimmune gene, while the other's diet kept it silenced.",
      "Chronic stress (cortisol), environmental toxins (BPA), and sugar literally strip methyl groups off DNA, turning ON disease-promoting genes."
    ],
    "epigenetic_rescue": [
      "Methyl-donors in the diet (Choline, Folate, B12 from eggs, leafy greens, and meat) provide the chemical tags needed to keep bad genes SILENCED.",
      "Polyphenols (Curcumin from turmeric, EGCG from green tea) act as powerful histone deacetylase (HDAC) inhibitors, physically unspooling DNA to turn ON antioxidant and longevity genes."
    ],
    "related_nodes": ["ENV_ENDOCRINE_DISRUPTORS_001", "STR_CHRONIC_001", "NUT_METHYLATION_001"]
  },
